description: {'_content': "Back in the day when I was young there was no internets. So when you would travel you had books to get some information. Lonely Planets. But there was nothing in there. So if you would fly to some place, the entire thing was an adventure. You would explore some new stuff not only to yourself but you would explore stuff for mankind. Nowadays I would check the internets. Oh I want to go there. I need to see that too. Your entire agenda fills up with stuff from the internets. But you're already seeing those thing, on your screen. When you are actually there its the same shit, same toilet. Couple of months ago I was at Paris La Defense and I wanted to go to city centre to see some internets shit but I sticked around La Defense. All kinds of interesting things there that I didn't check on the internets. I was exploring again. I was alive. So.... new strategy boys and girls. I select one or two items I want to see from the internets. The remain of my time is open. Open for exploration. Open for adventures. Open for exictement. Excitment. How do you write the word GD? You see what's going on? I don't know the word not-no-mo' because my life has become too boring. Excitement! There, there you have it. So forget the internets. Only LOSERS on the internets. The internets kill your brain and the peoples on the internets don't know shit. I know. Only I know. You listen to ME now. I am your Sensei. The internets have stolen my dreams. How DARE you? Terminate your internets! :)"}

description: {'_content': 'Les pontes sont au nombre de 3 √† 6 par an, de mai √† octobre, et les ≈ìufs, 2 le plus souvent (rarement un seul ou 3), sont allong√©s blancs et luisants. C'est le m√¢le qui va chercher les mat√©riaux de nidification (brindilles, paille et brins d'herbe et c'est la femelle qui construit le nid. La dur√©e d'incubation est de 17 √† 19 jours et est assur√©e par la femelle principalement, bien que le m√¢le assure la rel√®ve de temps en temps. Les pigeonneaux naissent avec un duvet plus ou moins jaun√¢tre mais rarissime. Contrairement aux petits des poules qui ressemblent d√®s leur naissance √† de petites boules de mimosa, le petit pigeon a l'air tout chauve et est incapable de s'assumer tout seul. De plus il a les yeux ferm√©s pendant au moins une semaine. La femelle et le m√¢le pigeon prodiguent ensemble tous les soins √† leur prog√©niture ; ils y consacrent d'ailleurs toute leur vie... Un bien bel exemple pour beaucoup d'humains ! Pigeonneau - Les jeunes pigeons sont d'abord nourris par du ¬´ lait de pigeon ¬ª, une substance secr√©t√©e par le jabot des adultes. Plus tard, avec des graines ramollies d√©pos√©es dans leur bec. Au bout d'un mois ils sont capables de quitter le nid, mais il faut attendre qu'ils aient cinq semaines pour qu'ils commencent √† voler. france-pigeon.fr/pigeon.htm __________________________________ There are 3 to 6 eggs each year, from May to October. Eggs, 2 most often (rarely one or 3), are elongated white and shiny. It is the male who fetches the nesting material (twigs, straw and blades of grass) and it is the female who builds the nest. The incubation period from 17 to 19 days and is ensured by the female mainly , although the male assures the relief from time to time. The young pigeons are born with a down more or less yellowish but extremely rare. Unlike small chickens that look like small mimosa balls from birth, the little pigeon looks bald and can not take care of itself. In addition he has his eyes closed for at least a week. The female and the male pigeon jointly lavish all the care on their offspring; they spend all their life to do so ... A good example for many humans beings! Young pigeons are first fed with "pigeon milk", a substance secreted by the crop of adults. Later, with soggy seeds deposited in their beaks. After one month they are able to leave the nest, but it is necessary to wait until they have five weeks to start flying. Translate from: france-pigeon.fr/pigeon.htm'}

"If you only knew the power of the Dark Side. ..."
"Hello, Will. I want to congratulate you on the job you did on Mr. Lounds. I admire that enormously ‚Äî oh, what a cunning boy you are!"
